 within and moves among literary, musical, and visual arts. Munby traces the legacy of badness in Rudolph Fisher and Chester Himes’s detective fiction and in Claude McKay, Julian Mayfield, and Donald Goines’s urban experience writing. Ranging from Peetie Wheatstraw’s gangster blues to gangsta rap, he also examines criminals in popular songs. Turning to the screen, the underworld films of Oscar Micheaux and Ralph Cooper, the 1970s blaxploitation cycle, and the 1990s hood movie come under his microscope as well. Ultimately, Munby concludes that this tradition has been a misunderstood aspect of African American civic life and that, rather than undermining black culture, it forms a rich and enduring response to being outcast in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican American arts. 0aAfrican Americans in popular culture. 0aCrime in popular culturezUnited States. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acrime, criminal, identity, understanding, self, african american, america, united states, usa, popular culture, media, black, myth, bias, discrimination, academic, scholarly, research, civil rights, rationale, harlem renaissance, contemporary, modern, history, historical, gangsta, literary, music, musical, arts, artistic, interdisciplinary, modernity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226550374423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226550374/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles